</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[264,1323,1825,1891]" lastBlockId="3.[264,1323,284,430]" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="20" pageId="2" pageNumber="19">
Currently 
<number box="[383,398,1825,1851]" pageId="2" pageNumber="19" value="6.0">6</number>
described species are assigned to the genus (
<bibRefCitation author="Platnick" box="[924,1099,1825,1851]" pageId="2" pageNumber="28" refString="Platnick, N. I. (2005) World spider catalog version, 6.5. Available from http: // research. amnh. org / entomology / spiders / catalog / SALTICIDAE. html. (accessed 15 March 2006)" type="journal article" year="2005">
Platnick, 
<number box="[1036,1099,1825,1851]" pageId="2" pageNumber="19" value="2005.0">2005</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). The palpus of the 
<typeStatus box="[264,314,1865,1891]" pageId="2" pageNumber="19">type</typeStatus>
species (
<taxonomicName authority="Simon" authorityName="Simon" box="[431,703,1865,1891]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Lapsias" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="estebanensis">
<emphasis box="[431,614,1865,1890]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="19">L. estebanensis</emphasis>
Simon
</taxonomicName>
) is shown in 
<figureCitation box="[875,948,1865,1891]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[264,368,1592,1616]" captionTargetBox="[605,986,558,1581]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[601,986,547,1589]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Lapsias estebanensis Simon, left palpus of male holotype. e = embolus, ma = median apophysis." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/173062/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="19">
Fig. 
<number box="[933,948,1865,1891]" pageId="2" pageNumber="19" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
(
<typeStatus box="[967,1019,1865,1891]" pageId="2" pageNumber="19">type</typeStatus>
specimen, 
<collectionCode LSID="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34988" box="[1159,1254,1865,1891]" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34988" name="Museum National d'Histoire Naturelle" pageId="2" pageNumber="19">MNHN</collectionCode>
). The palpi are similar in Simon's four species (
<typeStatus box="[765,817,284,310]" pageId="3" pageNumber="20">type</typeStatus>
specimens in 
<collectionCode LSID="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34988" box="[991,1081,284,310]" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34988" name="Museum National d'Histoire Naturelle" pageId="3" pageNumber="20">MNHN</collectionCode>
examined; 
<bibRefCitation author="Galiano" pageId="3" pageNumber="27" refString="Galiano, M. E. (1963) Las especies americanas de aranas de la familia Salticidae descriptas por Eugene Simon: Redescripciones basadas en los ejemplares tipicos. Physis, Buenos Aires, 23, 273 - 470." type="journal article" year="1963">
Galiano, 
<number box="[264,326,324,350]" pageId="3" pageNumber="20" value="1963.0">1963</number>
</bibRefCitation>
), with a small curved fingerlike median apophysis and a fairly short embolus. As in other lapsiines, the females of 
<taxonomicName box="[666,757,364,389]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Lapsias" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="3" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[666,757,364,389]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="20">Lapsias</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName authority="Simon" authorityName="Simon" box="[783,1002,364,390]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Lapsias" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="3" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ciliatus">
<emphasis box="[783,909,364,389]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="20">L. ciliatus</emphasis>
Simon
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Simon" authorityName="Simon" box="[1076,1322,364,390]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Lapsias" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="3" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cyrboides">
<emphasis box="[1076,1230,364,389]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="20">L. cyrboides</emphasis>
Simon
</taxonomicName>
examined) have a claw on the tarsus of the palpus.
</paragraph>
